{
  "text": "We assessed prenatal selenium status based on selenium concentrations in maternal erythrocytes, which, like hair selenium, represents average intake over a longer time period (approximately 2-3 months; [CITATION_1] ) than plasma selenium (a few weeks; N\u00e8ve 1995) or urine (a few days; [CITATION_2] . For a subsample of the study population (n = 98) we previously measured plasma selenium in the beginning of the second trimester [CITATION_3] , and we found a strong correlation with selenium in the erythrocytes [r s = 0:69, p < 0:001 [CITATION_4] ]. In that sample, approximately 60% had concentrations <60 lg=L, indicating selenium deficiency [CITATION_5] , which is in accord with the reported low selenium content in the agricultural soil in Bangladesh [CITATION_6] ). Consequently, we did not have sufficient numbers of highly exposed women to evaluate potential toxic effects of such selenium levels. The children in the present cohort appeared to have somewhat higher selenium status than their mothers, based on the urine and erythrocyte concentrations measured in another subsample of 488 mother-child (9 y of age) pairs [CITATION_7] ).",
